Why not a recursive complete search? Something like the following should work:
It works like this:
If you want to generate all possible string of length `n` you could either insert either a `&#39;Y&#39;` or a `&#39;-&#39;` in the first position. 
Once you made your decision you can append your choice to all possible combinations of  length `n-1`.

Here is it a possible implementation that you can try [online][1]:

    vector&lt;string&gt;  generate_p(const int n){
        vector&lt;string&gt; ans;
        if(n==0)
        {
            ans.push_back(&quot;&quot;);   
        }
        else
        {
            auto v = generate_p(n-1);    
            for(size_t i = 0 ; i &lt; v.size() ; i++){
                ans.push_back(&quot;Y&quot;+v[i]);
                ans.push_back(&quot;-&quot;+v[i]);
            }
        }
        return ans;   
    }


----------


Another approach would be to notice that for each position you have two choice: &#39;Y&#39; or &#39;-&#39; like you have for a binary number where you can choose between &#39;1&#39; or &#39;0&#39;. 
So, if you list all numbers from `&#39;0000&#39;` to `&#39;1111&#39;` in base `&#39;2&#39;` you get all your combos. I leave that as an exercise to you. 

  [1]: https://wandbox.org/permlink/H0DwdUCa9p96m6ZD

You can use the algo [next_permutation][1]


    #include &lt;algorithm&gt;
    #include &lt;string&gt;
    #include &lt;iostream&gt;
        
    int main()
    {
        std::string s = &quot;____&quot;;
        std::string per;
        int count = 1;
        // first combi 
        std::cout &lt;&lt; s &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
        for (auto i=0;i&lt;s.size();i++)
        {
        //character for replacement 
        s[i] = &#39;y&#39;;
        per = s;
        std::sort(per.begin(), per.end());
        do {
            std::cout &lt;&lt; per &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
            count++;
        } while(std::next_permutation(per.begin(), per.end()));
        }
         std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Number of Combination is &quot;  &lt;&lt; count&lt;&lt;&#39;\n&#39;;
    }


